The '''black-and-red broadbill''' ('''''Cymbirhynchus macrorhynchos''''') is a [[species]] of [[bird]] in the typical broadbill family, [[Eurylaimidae]]. It is the [[Monotypic taxon|only species]] in the [[genus]] '''''Cymbirhynchus'''''. A large, distinctive bird, it has [[maroon]] underparts, black upperparts, a maroon neck-band, and white bars on the wings. It also has a large, two-colored, blue-and-yellow bill. The species shows slight [[sexual dimorphism]], with females being smaller than males. No other bird in its range resembles it, though the [[black-and-yellow broadbill]] has a similar [[Bird vocalization|call]].

The species is found in [[Brunei]], [[Cambodia]], Indonesia, [[Laos]], Malaysia, Myanmar, Singapore, Thailand, and Vietnam. Inhabiting lowland [[riparian forest]] throughout its range, it can also adapt quite well to disturbed habitat, such as [[Secondary forest|secondary forest growth]] and degraded habitat near rivers. The black-and-red broadbill is mainly [[Insectivore|insectivorous]], supplementing its diet with aquatic creatures such as [[Mollusca|mollusks]], [[snail]]s, [[fish]], and [[crustacean]]s. It also takes leaves and seeds incidentally.

Breeding takes place during the dry season throughout its range, with the nest being a large, conspicuous structure that usually hangs over water. [[Bird nest|Nests]] are built by both sexes, out of creepers, fungal [[hypha]]e, moss, and other plant matter. Eggs are laid in [[Clutch (eggs)|clutches]] of two or three, occasionally with a fourth [[runt]] egg, and [[Egg incubation|incubated]] by both parents. The black-and-red broadbill is evaluated as a [[least-concern species]] by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] due to its large range and the lack of a severe decrease in its global population. However, the species has experienced declines in several parts of its range, and may face threats due to deforestation, trapping for the songbird trade, and hunting.

== Taxonomy and systematics ==
The German naturalist [[Johann Friedrich Gmelin]] described the species as ''[[Todus]] macrorhynchos'' in 1788,<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Linné |first1=Carl von |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/10285 |title=Systema naturae per regna tria naturae: secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis. |last2=Gmelin |first2=Johann Friedrich |last3=Beer |first3=Georg Emanuel |date=1788 |publisher=Georg Emanuel Beer |volume=1 |location=Leipzig |page=446 |language=la |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.545 |oclc=8208636 |access-date=13 July 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210725140703/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/10285 |archive-date=25 July 2021 |url-status=live |via=[[Biodiversity Heritage Library]] |doi-access=free}}</ref> based on a Bornean specimen that was originally described as a "great-billed tody" by the English naturalist [[John Latham (ornithologist)|John Latham]] in 1782.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Latham |first=John |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/105229 |title=A General Synopsis of Birds |date=1782 |publisher=Printed for Benj. White |series=2 |volume=1 |location=London |pages=664–665 |language=en |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.49894 |oclc=3180970 |access-date=13 July 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210713054338/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/105229 |archive-date=13 July 2021 |url-status=live |via=[[Biodiversity Heritage Library]] |doi-access=free}}</ref> Later, in 1790, the species was named ''Todus nasutus'' by Latham, as he had not provided scientific names in his first description.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Calaby|first=J. H.|year=2006|title=Latham, John (1740–1837)|chapter=John Latham (1740–1837) |url=https://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/latham-john-2333/text3037|url-status=live|publisher=National Centre of Biography, Australian National University|access-date=4 November 2021|archive-date=4 November 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211104120917/https://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/latham-john-2333/text3037}}</ref> However, [[Principle of Priority|priority]] is afforded to Gmelin's name. The [[genus]] ''Cymbirhynchus'' was erected for this species in 1830 by [[Nicholas Aylward Vigors|Nicolas Vigors]] and [[Thomas Horsfield]].<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Cottrell |first1=G. William |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/50584 |title=Check-list of Birds of the World |last2=Greenway |first2=James C. |last3=Mayr |first3=Ernst |last4=Paynter |first4=Raymond A. |last5=Peters |first5=James Lee |last6=Traylor |first6=Melvin A. |last7=University |first7=Harvard |date=1951 |publisher=Harvard University Press |volume=7 |location=Cambridge |language=en |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.14581 |oclc=12228458 |access-date=9 September 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210909033711/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/50584 |archive-date=9 September 2021 |url-status=live |via=[[Biodiversity Heritage Library]] |doi-access=free}}</ref>

The generic name is from the Greek {{lang|grc|κυμβη}} ({{lang|grc-Latn|kumbē}}), which could mean either "small boat" or "an unknown bird", and {{lang|grc|ῥυγχος}} ({{lang|grc-Latn|rhunkhos}}), meaning bill. The specific name ''macrorhynchos'' comes from the [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] {{lang|grc|μακρορρυγχος}} ({{lang|grc-Latn|makrorrunkhos}}), meaning long-billed.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Jobling |first=James A. |url=https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling |title=Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names |publisher=Christopher Helm |year=2010 |isbn=978-1-4081-3326-2 |location=London |pages=138, 236}}</ref> "Black-and-red broadbill" is the official English [[common name]] designated by the [[International Ornithologists' Union]];<ref name="ioc" /> other common names in English include black-red broadbill and black and white broadbill.<ref name=":22">{{Cite web |title=''Cymbirhynchus macrorhynchos'' (Black-and-red Broadbill) |url=https://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=2F81A394BE6ECFFD |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210627064926/https://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=2F81A394BE6ECFFD |archive-date=27 June 2021 |access-date=2021-06-19 |website=Avibase}}</ref> The species is also known by the names {{lang|th|Nok Phaya Paak Kwaang thong daeng}} in [[Thai language|Thai]],<ref name=":12">{{Cite book |last=Wells |first=David R. |title=The Birds of the Thai-Malay Peninsula Vol. 2: Passerines |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |year=2010 |isbn=978-1-4081-3313-2 |location=London |pages=50–55}}</ref> {{lang|vi|Chim Mỏ rộng đỏ}} and {{lang|vi|Mỏ rộng đỏ}} in [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]],<ref name=":22">{{Cite web |title=''Cymbirhynchus macrorhynchos'' (Black-and-red Broadbill) |url=https://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=2F81A394BE6ECFFD |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210627064926/https://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=2F81A394BE6ECFFD |archive-date=27 June 2021 |access-date=2021-06-19 |website=Avibase}}</ref> {{lang|id|Sempur-hujan sungai}} in [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]],<ref name=":0" /> and {{lang|ms|Takau rakit}} and {{lang|ms|burong tĕrajan}} in [[Malay language|Malay]] (with the latter name only being used in the state of [[Kelantan]]).<ref name=":12">{{Cite book |last=Wells |first=David R. |title=The Birds of the Thai-Malay Peninsula Vol. 2: Passerines |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |year=2010 |isbn=978-1-4081-3313-2 |location=London |pages=50–55}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Berwick |first1=E. J. H. |date=1953 |title=Some Kelantan bird names |journal=Journal of the Malayan Branch of the Royal Asiatic Society |volume=26 |issue=1 |pages=140–144 |jstor=41502910}}</ref>

The black-and-red broadbill is the [[Monotypic taxon|only species]] in the genus ''Cymbirhynchus,'' in the typical broadbill [[Family (taxonomy)|family]] [[Eurylaimidae]], a family of ten tropical species native to [[Southeast Asia]].<ref name="ioc" /> Based on a 2017 study by the Brazilian researcher Alexandre Selvatti and colleagues, its closest relative is the [[silver-breasted broadbill]]. These two species are most closely related to the ''[[Eurylaimus]]'' broadbills, and all three genera form a [[sister clade]] to the genus ''[[Sarcophanops]]''. This clade is sister to one formed by the [[long-tailed broadbill]] and [[dusky broadbill]]. Both of these clades are sister to the [[Grauer's broadbill]]. The following cladogram shows [[Phylogenetics|phylogenetic]] relationships among the Eurylaimidae, based on the above study:{{Efn|The study did not include the [[Visayan broadbill]], which was formerly considered [[conspecific]] with the [[wattled broadbill]]. Additionally, it treated the [[grey-lored broadbill]] as being conspecific with the [[silver-breasted broadbill]].<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Cottrell|first1=G. William|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14480346#page/23/mode/1up|title=Check-list of birds of the world|last2=Greenway|first2=James C.|last3=Mayr|first3=Ernst|last4=Paynter|first4=Raymond A.|last5=Peters|first5=James Lee|last6=Traylor|first6=Melvin A.|publisher=[[Harvard University Press]]|year=1951|volume=7|location=Cambridge|page=9|language=en|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=19 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220119043215/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14480346#page/23/mode/1up|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Selvatti-et-al" />|name=}}<ref name="Selvatti-et-al">{{Cite journal |last1=Selvatti |first1=A. P. |last2=Galvão |first2=A. |last3=Pereira |first3=A. G. |last4=Pedreira Gonzaga |first4=L. |last5=Russo |first5=C. A. D. M. |date=2017 |title=An African origin of the Eurylaimides (Passeriformes) and the successful diversification of the ground-foraging pittas (Pittidae) |journal=Molecular Biology and Evolution |volume=34 |issue=2 |pages=483–499 |doi=10.1093/molbev/msw250 |pmid=28069777 |doi-access=free}}</ref>

